According to a new report from Intel Market Research, the global Textile Radio Frequency Dryers market was valued at USD 382 million in 2025 and is projected to reach USD 646 million by 2034, growing at a robust CAGR of 8.0% during the forecast period (2025–2034). The rapid expansion of the textile sector, combined with heightened focus on energy efficiency and process automation, has positioned radio‑frequency (RF) drying technology as a critical enabler for modern textile manufacturing.

Textile Radio Frequency (RF) Dryers are highly specialized systems that employ radio‑frequency energy to generate heat directly within fibers, yarns, and finished fabrics. This direct heating mechanism enables rapid moisture removal while preserving fabric integrity, reducing shrinkage, and lowering overall thermal stresses. Compared with conventional steam or convection dryers, RF dryers achieve faster processing times, lower water usage, and significant reductions in energy consumption-attributes that resonate strongly with manufacturers seeking to boost throughput and improve sustainability credentials.

